# Kaggle Machine Learning course

This notebook is an Apache Spark adaptation of the Machine Learning course available at [Kaggle](https://www.kaggle.com/). It presumes that there is a folder called `data` in the working directory of the notebook and that the `data` folder contains the required Ames housing data which can be downloaded from https://ww2.amstat.org/publications/jse/v19n3/decock/AmesHousing.txt.

We will begin by loading and exploring the data a little bit to see how it is structured.

The reason this is not a good approach to modeling is that we are evaluating the model on data it has already used to train on. The model could be overfitted to our data and give much worse predictions on new data. A better procedure would be to hold out some of the data as a *validation set* and only fit the model on the remaining *training set*. We will try this approach now and see how our model changes with these sets.

paragraphs.text:
%md
## Advanced topics

That covers the basics of creating and evaluating machine learning models. We will now move on to more advanced topics and begin by exploring the problem of handling missing values. First we need to find which columns actually contain some missing data. We will then add a couple of them, impute values and train a new random forest model with these extra columns with imputed values. An even simpler way of handling missing values would be to simply drop all columns with missing values but in our case this would simply give us our old model.

import org.apache.spark.sql.types._
import scala.util.Random

// Let's first select all numerical fields in our data.
val numericCols = iowaData.schema.filter(x => x.dataType == IntegerType || x.dataType == DoubleType)
val numericData = iowaData.select(numericCols.map(x => col(x.name)): _*)

// Next, let's find some numeric columns containing missing data.
val nullCols = numericCols.filter(x => numericData.select(x.name).where(col(x.name).isNull).count > 0)

// Select a couple of random columns with missing data (seed set to 0 for reproducibility in this case)
val rand = new Random(0)
val randNullCols = rand.shuffle(nullCols).take(10)
val nullData = numericData.select(randNullCols.map(x => col(x.name)): _*)
nullData.cache

// The imputer requires doubles, hence why we cast all the integers to doubles in the previous step.

import org.apache.spark.ml.feature.Imputer

import org.apache.spark.ml.feature.{StringIndexer, OneHotEncoderEstimator}

// Let's treat the categorical data, first with a string indexer and then with the one-hot encoder.
val indexers = randCatCols.map{x => 
    new StringIndexer().setInputCol(x.name).setOutputCol(x.name + "_index").setHandleInvalid("keep").fit(catTrainData)
}
val (indexedTrainData, indexedTestData) = indexers.foldLeft((catTrainData, catTestData))((dfs,indexer) => (indexer.transform(dfs._1), indexer.transform(dfs._2)))

val encoder = new OneHotEncoderEstimator().setInputCols(randCatCols.map(x => x.name + "_index").toArray).setOutputCols(randCatCols.map(x => x.name + "_encoded").toArray).fit(indexedTrainData)
val (encodedTrainData, encodedTestData) = (encoder.transform(indexedTrainData).drop(randCatCols.map(x => x.name) ++ randCatCols.map(x => x.name + "_index"): _*), 
    encoder.transform(indexedTestData).drop(randCatCols.map(x => x.name) ++ randCatCols.map(x => x.name + "_index"): _*))
encodedTrainData.cache
encodedTestData.cache

import org.apache.spark.ml.regression.{GBTRegressor, GBTRegressionModel}

val gbtRegressor = new GBTRegressor().setLabelCol("SalePrice").setSeed(0).setMaxIter(10)
val gbtModel = gbtRegressor.fit(trainData)
val gbtPredictions = gbtModel.transform(testData)
val gbtMAE = evaluator.evaluate(gbtPredictions)
println(s"Mean Absolute error of the gbt model:\t$gbtMAE")

(25 to 40).foreach{ bins =>
     val gbtRegressor = new GBTRegressor().setLabelCol("SalePrice").setSeed(0).setMaxIter(10).setMaxDepth(7).setMaxBins(bins)
     val gbtModel = gbtRegressor.fit(trainData)
     val gbtPredictions = gbtModel.transform(testData)
     val gbtMAE = evaluator.evaluate(gbtPredictions)
     println(s"Max bins:\t$bins\t\tMAE:\t$gbtMAE")
}

%md
Our best model so far is achieved by using a depth of 7 and 26 bins. Note that this is not a very good way of tuning hyperparameters, for instance it could be that a model with depth 6 and 30 bins would be even better.

So far so good but we have achieved this through many, many steps. In order to save a lot of time and typing we can use a *pipeline*. Pipelines allow us to string together everything we have done, including handling of data and training of models, into one convenient procedure. To illustrate the power of pipelines we will create a gradient boosted tree model using all our available data, including all handling of missing data and encoding of categorical data.
